<Layout title="Getting started">
  <article class="doc">
    <DocsNav active="getting-started" />
    <h1>Getting started</h1>
    <p class="intro">Install the native lawlint CLI, point it at a document, and get a focused list of things worth revising.</p>
    <h2>Install lawlint</h2>
    <pre>curl -fsSL https://lawlint.com/install.sh | sh</pre>
    <p>For Windows, run <code>irm https://lawlint.com/install.ps1 | iex</code> in PowerShell. You can also download a platform-specific CLI archive from the <a href="/download">downloads page</a>.</p>
    <h2>Build from source</h2>
    <pre>git clone https://github.com/sethtjf/lawlint
cd lawlint
cargo build --release -p lawlint-cli</pre>
    <p>Building from source is useful for development or for platforms without a published archive.</p>
    <h2>Run the CLI</h2>
    <pre>lawlint contract.md
lawlint brief.docx --fix
cat memo.txt | lawlint - --format json</pre>
    <p>Linting needs no configuration and runs entirely offline. Markdown files automatically skip fenced code blocks (for piped Markdown, add <code>--markdown</code>). Word documents lint directly; <code>--fix</code> writes machine-applicable fixes back as native tracked changes with a review comment per fix.</p>
    <h2>Set up AI features</h2>
    <pre>lawlint init</pre>
    <p>The init walkthrough configures which AI model powers lawlint's optional AI features — the tier-3 judge (<code>--judge</code>) and personal rule mining (<code>lawlint learn</code>). Hosted providers (Anthropic — recommended, OpenAI, Azure Foundry) require an API key, which is stored in a user-level credential file, never in your project. Until a model is configured, AI features exit with guidance instead of running; nothing is ever downloaded silently. Local models remain available as an explicit advanced choice after acknowledging their resource and quality constraints. Selections are written to <code>.lawlint/config.json</code>, which the CLI discovers from the current directory upward.</p>
    <h2>Scoring</h2>
    <p>Every result includes a human-likeness score from 0 to 100. The score aggregates only <em>detection</em>-intent rules — the subset corpus-validated to distinguish AI-generated from authentic human legal prose. <em>Style</em>-intent rules (Oxford comma, semicolons, sentence length, the Orwell rules) still report findings and participate in <code>--fix</code>, but never charge the score. Among detection rules, each diagnostic charges a penalty—5 points per error, 3 per warning, and 1 per info—normalized per 1,000 words, so the score reflects issue density rather than document length. The score decays smoothly as penalty density rises, and density rules such as <code>no-hedging</code> and <code>no-em-dash-overuse</code> charge in proportion to how far past their threshold the text runs.</p>
    <h2>Exit codes</h2>
    <ul><li><code>0</code> when no errors are found and the warning limit is not exceeded.</li><li><code>1</code> when an error is found or <code>--max-warnings</code> is exceeded.</li></ul>
